## Package Group

The Package group works on the part of GitLab concerning the [Package
stage], which integrates with [GitLab's CI/CD product](/direction/ops/).
Our mission is to create a secure environment where both source code and dependencies can live by
allowing you to publish, consume, and discover packages of a large variety of languages and platforms
all in one place.
The package group is a [Fullstack team](https://about.gitlab.com/handbook/engineering/#fullstack-teams) which means that all the engineers, Frontend and Backend, report to a single [Fullstack Engineering Manager](https://about.gitlab.com/job-families/engineering/development/management/fullstack-manager/). The intention of using this model is to increase efficiency and drive results by building a process that supports all team members towards our goals. Primarily, this means that all engineers participate in conversations in the group and contribute broadly to group process iteration.

The package group is made up of 3 functional teams:
- Two Go engineers primarily responsible for
  - [Container Registry](https://about.gitlab.com/direction/ops/#container-registry/)
  - [Helm Chart Registry](https://about.gitlab.com/direction/ops/#helm-chart-registry)
- Three Ruby engineers who are primarily responsible for:
  - [Package Registry](https://about.gitlab.com/direction/ops/#package-registry)
  - [Dependency Proxy](https://about.gitlab.com/direction/ops/#dependency-proxy)
  - [Dependency Firewall](https://about.gitlab.com/direction/ops/#dependency-firewall)
  - [Git LFS](https://about.gitlab.com/direction/ops/#git-lfs)
- One frontend engineer who is primarily responsible for
  - Implementation of User Experience spanning all categories

Due to these small functional teams, the Package group deliverables are sometimes more at risk given that there are fewer people who can help out.

For more details about the vision for this area of the product, see the [product vision] page.

